This notebook tries new parameters to deal with datasets of 1 GeV cut and minimum 5 hits per tracks.

Define run config¶

In [3]:
# == INPUT CONFIG

# path to the input dataset
path = '/tmp/hpt-1.0_399/event000001000' 
# whether or not to add missing doublets to the input
add_missing = False 

# == RUN CONFIG

model_class = Qallse # model class to use
extra_config = dict( # configuration arguments overriding the defaults
    tplet_max_curv = 8E-4,  # instead of 5E-3 / 0.005
    tplet_max_drz  = 0.1,   # instead of 0.2
    qplet_max_dcurv = 1E-4, # instead of 5E-4 / 0.0005
)

In [5]:
# load data
dw = DataWrapper.from_path(path)
doublets = pd.read_csv(path + '-doublets.csv')
if add_missing:
    doublets = dw.add_missing_doublets(doublets)
else:
    p, r, ms = dw.compute_score(doublets)
    print(f'got {len(doublets)}.')
    print(f'  Input precision (%): {p*100:.4f}, recall (%): {r*100:.4f}, missing: {len(ms)}')

got 101373.
  Input precision (%): 2.8874, recall (%): 99.1531, missing: 25

Build & run¶

In [6]:
%%time

# instantiate qallse
model = model_class(dw, **extra_config)
# build the qubo
model.build_model(doublets=doublets)
Q = model.to_qubo()

Plot the results¶

You have the following at your disposal:

iplot_results(dw, final_doublets, missings, dims=list('xy'))
iplot_results_tracks(dw, final_doublets, missings, dims=list('zr'))
iplot_results_any(dw, dw.real_doublets, dims=list('xy'))

For 3D plots, simply define dims as 3-dimensional. For example:

iplot_results(dw, final_doublets, missings, dims=list('zxy'))
In [10]:
iplot_results(dw, final_doublets, missings, dims=list('xy'))

In [27]:
v_strengths, i_strengths = [], []
_ = [v_strengths.append(qplet.strength) 
       if dw.is_real_xplet(qplet.hit_ids()) 
       else i_strengths.append(qplet.strength)
     for qplet in model.quadruplets]

fig, axes = plt.subplots(1,2, figsize=(12, 6))
for ax, normed in zip(axes, [False, True]):
    ax.hist(i_strengths, alpha=0.3, color='crimson', label='invalid', density=normed)
    ax.hist(v_strengths, alpha=0.3, color='darkcyan', label='valid', density=normed)
    ax.legend()
plt.tight_layout()
